{"id":"1605.01705","submitter":"David Schleicher","authors":"David G. Schleicher and Matthew M. Knight","title":"The Extremely Low Activity Comet 209P/LINEAR During Its Extraordinary\n  Close Approach in 2014","comments":"22 pages, including 4 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.3847/0004-6256/152/4/89","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.EP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We present results from our observing campaign of Comet 209P/LINEAR during\nits exceptionally close approach to Earth during May of 2014, the third\nsmallest perigee of any comet in two centuries. These circumstances permitted\nus to pursue several studies of this intrinsically faint object, including\nmeasurements of gas and dust production rates, searching for coma morphology,\nand direct detection of the nucleus to measure its properties. Indeed, we\nsuccessfully measured the lowest water production rates of an intact comet in\nover 35 years and a corresponding smallest active area, ~0.007 km^2. When\ncombined with the nucleus size found from radar (Howell et al. 2014), this also\nyields the smallest active fraction for any comet, ~0.024%. In all, this\nstrongly suggests that 209P/LINEAR is on its way to becoming an inert object.\nThe nucleus was detected but could not easily be disentangled from the inner\ncoma due to seeing variations and changing spatial scales. Even so, we were\nable to measure a double-peaked lightcurve consistent with the shorter of two\nviable rotational periods found by Hergenrother (2014). Radial profiles of the\ndust coma are quite steep, similar to that observed for some other very anemic\ncomets and suggestive that vaporizing icy grains are present.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 5 May 2016 19:41:21 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-10-05"}
